  discoveryByAudience:{
    "IT Manager":["Do you currently have 24/7 coverage for your environment — what happens when a threat triggers at 2am on a Saturday?", "How long does it typically take your team to investigate a high-severity alert end to end?", "Have you gone through a cyber insurance renewal recently — what controls did they ask for that you could not demonstrate?", "How many security alerts does your team receive per day, and what percentage do you actually investigate?", "If your primary security person left tomorrow, what would happen to your threat monitoring capability?"],
    "Security Engineer":["What does your current detection and response coverage look like outside of business hours — who is watching the queue?", "How are you correlating endpoint, network, and identity telemetry today — separate tools or a unified platform?", "When you investigate a threat, how long does it take to get from the initial alert to a confirmed root cause?", "What third-party tools are you running today that you would need an MDR service to ingest and correlate?", "Have you had a scenario where a threat was active in your environment for days before detection — what caused the dwell time?"],
    "CTO / CISO":["How are you currently demonstrating to your board and insurer that you have active 24/7 threat monitoring in place?", "What is your current measured Mean Time to Detect and Mean Time to Respond — and how do those compare to industry benchmarks?", "Have you evaluated the cost of building a comparable internal SOC capability versus outsourcing MDR?", "What is your organisation's cyber incident response plan — and who owns the execution of that plan in an active breach scenario?", "Does your cyber insurance policy include requirements for 24/7 monitoring or documented incident response capability?"],
    "MSP / Partner SE":["Are you currently offering a managed detection and response service tier to your customers — or referring them elsewhere for that?", "What is your current process when a customer has an active security incident — who responds and how quickly?", "How many of your customers have asked about 24/7 security monitoring in the last 12 months?", "Are you able to scale MDR-level coverage across your customer base without hiring additional security analysts?", "What would it mean for your customer retention and renewal rates if you could guarantee 24/7 threat response?"],
  },
  objections:[
    {q:"We have an internal SOC — why pay for MDR?",a:"MDR and an internal SOC aren't mutually exclusive. Most customers use MDR as a force multiplier — we cover nights, weekends, and overflow while your team handles strategic work. MDR Complete can fully replace tier 1/2 SOC functions, freeing headcount for architecture and engineering. The math usually works: sub-$100K/year vs. multiple analyst salaries plus tooling plus training plus attrition. And our MDR team brings experience across 30,000+ customer environments, pattern-matching capability no single-customer SOC can replicate."},
    {q:"What stops MDR from taking actions we didn't want?",a:"Notify Only and Collaborate modes specifically prevent actions without your approval. Even in Authorize mode, every action is logged with a written justification from the analyst — you have complete auditability. You also define the rules of engagement during onboarding and can change them at any time. Think of it like setting a surgery protocol: you define what the team can do in an emergency before one occurs, so response isn't delayed by approval chains at 3 AM."},
    {q:"We already have SIEM — isn't MDR redundant?",a:"SIEM gives you data and dashboards. MDR gives you humans who act on that data 24/7. SIEMs generate enormous alert volumes — industry average is 97% of alerts never investigated. MDR reduces that gap. We can also ingest your SIEM telemetry as a data source — so it's additive, not competitive. The ROI question is: does your team currently investigate every SIEM alert within the hour? If not, MDR fills that gap."}
  ],
  competitors:[
    {name:"vs CrowdStrike Falcon Complete",points:["Falcon Complete is primarily endpoint-anchored; Sophos MDR covers endpoint, network, email, cloud, identity, M365 natively","350+ third-party integrations vs. CrowdStrike's tighter coupling to Falcon stack","Direct M365 response actions (May 2025): analysts act inside your M365 tenant — Falcon Complete has no equivalent","Sophos MDR pricing is accessible for mid-market; Falcon Complete targets enterprise spend"]},
    {name:"vs Arctic Wolf",points:["Sophos brings proprietary endpoint, firewall, email, and NDR telemetry — Arctic Wolf is primarily SIEM/log aggregation","Sophos X-Ops + CTU (Secureworks) gives deeper adversary intelligence than Arctic Wolf Concierge model","MDR Complete includes full incident response SLA; Arctic Wolf Concierge notifies but limits active response","Sophos MDR is G2 #1 rated in 2026 vs. Arctic Wolf; Gartner Peer Insights score consistently higher"]}
  ],
  specs:[["Service Tiers","MDR Essentials (monitoring + alerting), MDR Complete (full incident response)"],["SLA – Critical","60-min response on 90% of high-severity cases (MDR Complete)"],["SOC Locations","7 global SOCs, 24/7/365 coverage"],["Response Modes","Authorize, Collaborate, Notify Only — configurable per severity level"],["Third-Party Integrations","350+ telemetry providers across endpoint, firewall, identity, cloud, email"],["Data Retention","Standard 90 days; Extended 1 year available"],["M365 Actions","Disable sign-in, terminate sessions, remove inbox rules (May 2025, all tiers)"],["Breach Protection Warranty","Up to $1M for MDR Complete customers maintaining health score threshold"]]
