    {
      id:"mob_compliancepolicies",
      name:"Compliance Policies",
      preview:"Device compliance rules — OS version, screen lock, jailbreak detection, prohibited apps, encryption enforcement",
      what:"Compliance Policies define the conditions a device must meet to be considered compliant with corporate security policy — minimum OS version requirements, screen lock enforcement, jailbreak and root detection, prohibited application checks, device encryption status, and maximum time since last check-in. Non-compliant devices can trigger automated responses including push notification to the user, conditional access block via Azure AD or Okta, and administrator alert.",
      talk:"\"Compliance Policies are where mobile security becomes enforceable rather than advisory. Without a compliance policy, you can see which devices are jailbroken or have an outdated OS — but you cannot do anything about it automatically. With a compliance policy, a jailbroken iPhone is immediately flagged as non-compliant. If you have conditional access integrated with Azure AD, that device is automatically blocked from accessing corporate email and Microsoft 365 apps within minutes of the jailbreak being detected — no admin intervention needed. The user gets a notification explaining why they are blocked and what they need to do to restore access. That automated response is what turns mobile visibility into mobile enforcement.\"",
      points:[
        "Jailbreak and root detection — jailbroken iOS and rooted Android devices automatically flagged as non-compliant; conditional access block triggered",
        "Minimum OS version — devices below required OS version flagged as non-compliant; forces users to update before accessing corporate resources",
        "Conditional access integration — non-compliant devices automatically blocked from Azure AD, Okta, and M365 apps without administrator action",
        "Automated remediation notification — non-compliant user receives push notification explaining the violation and steps required to restore access"
      ],
      action:"Navigate to Compliance Policies. Open a policy and walk through the compliance rules — show jailbreak detection, OS version requirement, and screen lock enforcement. Show the automated response configuration — notification to user and conditional access block. Demonstrate what a non-compliant device looks like in the Devices list and how the block is applied through Azure AD integration."
    },
    {
      id:"mob_appgroups",
      name:"App Groups",
      preview:"Logical app groupings for targeted deployment — role-based app sets for different user populations",
      what:"App Groups allow apps to be organised into logical sets for deployment targeting — grouping all apps required for a specific role or department and assigning the entire group to a device group in a single action. This simplifies app management at scale by separating the app catalogue into role-appropriate bundles rather than assigning apps individually to thousands of devices.",
      talk:"\"App Groups solve the same problem for apps that Task Bundles solve for policies. A field sales team needs Salesforce, a VPN client, the corporate email app, and a PDF reader. A warehouse team needs a barcode scanning app, the inventory system, and a shift management app. Instead of assigning eight apps individually to each group, you create an App Group for each role and assign the group. When the role changes or a new app is added to the standard set, you update the App Group once and it applies to every device in that group automatically.\"",
      points:[
        "Role-based app sets — group all apps for a specific role or department and deploy them together rather than managing apps individually per device",
        "Single assignment action — assign an App Group to a device group and all apps in the set deploy simultaneously to all devices in that group",
        "Centralised app set management — update an App Group once when the standard app set changes; all associated devices receive the update automatically",
        "BYOD versus corporate separation — separate App Groups for BYOD and corporate devices; BYOD groups offer optional apps while corporate groups enforce mandatory ones"
      ],
      action:"Navigate to App Groups. Show an existing App Group and the apps it contains. Demonstrate assigning an App Group to a device group and show the resulting app deployment tasks queued in the Tasks screen. Show how modifying an App Group by adding a new mandatory app pushes the update to all associated devices."
    },
    {
      id:"mob_setup",
      name:"Setup",
      preview:"Mobile enrolment configuration — Apple DEP, Android Enterprise, BYOD enrollment, conditional access, Intune connector",
      what:"The Setup section is where Sophos Mobile is configured for your environment — connecting Apple Business Manager for DEP and VPP, configuring Android Enterprise with managed Google Play, setting up BYOD enrollment portal branding and authentication, configuring conditional access integration with Azure AD or Okta, and connecting the Intune MTD connector for organisations that use Intune for MDM and want to add Sophos for mobile threat detection.",
      talk:"\"Setup is where the integrations that make Mobile Management enterprise-grade are configured. The Apple Business Manager connection enables zero-touch iOS enrollment — a brand new iPhone ships directly to an employee, the employee powers it on, it automatically enrolls in Sophos Mobile and downloads the corporate app configuration without IT ever touching the device. Android Enterprise with Zero Touch does the same for Android. The conditional access integration is what moves mobile from a visibility tool to an enforcement tool — a non-compliant or compromised device is automatically blocked from Azure AD resources without an admin having to manually revoke access. And the Intune connector is important for organisations that want to keep Intune as their MDM but add Sophos Mobile Threat Defense on top.\"",
      points:[
        "Apple DEP zero-touch enrollment — new iPhones enroll automatically when powered on; ships directly to employee without IT handling the device",
        "Android Enterprise — managed Google Play and zero-touch enrollment for corporate Android; app management without personal Google account",
        "Conditional access integration — Azure AD and Okta connectors enable automatic resource blocking for non-compliant or compromised devices",
        "Intune MTD connector — add Sophos mobile threat detection on top of an existing Intune MDM deployment without replacing Intune"
      ],
      action:"Navigate to Setup. Show the Apple Business Manager configuration and explain DEP zero-touch enrollment. Show the Android Enterprise managed Google Play connection. Walk through the Azure AD conditional access connector configuration. If relevant to the customer, show the Intune MTD connector setup and explain how it adds threat detection on top of existing Intune management."
    }
